    {
      "id": "memory-story",
      "durationMs": 18000,
      "narration": {
        "text": "The collector never stops the world and never moves an object. The app keeps rendering while a background thread marks and sweeps. That choice preserves native pointers and a two point four megabyte idle floor. Peak allocation churn fell below Java twenty five."
      },
      "actions": [
        {"type": "svg.show", "id": "memory-chart", "atMs": 200, "paths": {"landscape": "hotspot-memory-landscape.svg", "portrait": "hotspot-memory-portrait.svg"}, "bounds": {"x": 0.015, "y": 0.04, "width": 0.97, "height": 0.92}, "orientation": {"portrait": {"x": 0.06, "y": 0.06, "width": 0.88, "height": 0.88}}},
        {"type": "transition", "target": "memory-chart", "atMs": 200, "durationMs": 800, "effect": "morph", "easing": "ease-in-out"}
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "tagged-integers",
      "durationMs": 21500,
      "narration": {
        "text": "Autoboxing was the final big lever. On sixty-four-bit targets, Integer values fit inside tagged pointers. The low bit distinguishes them from real objects, so boxing allocates nothing and the collector ignores them. The tradeoff is identity, so locking on wrappers is rejected at build time."
      },
